<HEADLINE>
FT  20 OCT 94 / World Trade News: Thai price curb annoys Nestle
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VICTOR MALLET
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BANGKOK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Thailand has put instant coffee on a list of products subject to price
control, prompting veiled suggestions from Nestle, the Swiss foods
multinational, that foreign investors would take offence at such a backward
step on the road to free enterprise. Nestle, whose Thai subsidiary Quality
Coffee Products has more than 80 per cent of the local instant coffee
market, angered the government by raising prices by 10 per cent in July and
by refusing commerce ministry demands to reverse the price increase. This
week the cabinet authorised the ministry to put instant coffee on the list
of controlled consumer products. It had been removed two years ago along
with 100 other products as part of an economic liberalisation drive.
</TEXT>
