FT  20 OCT 94 / Balladur's call for truce spurned
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BUCHAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The French prime minister's call for a political ceasefire among fellow
conservatives yesterday drew a tart response from several of his
presidential rivals, with Mr Jacques Chirac spurning a bilateral truce.
Mr Edouard Balladur had invited Mr Chirac, the leader of his own RPR
Gaullist party, and ex-President Valery Giscard d'Estaing, head of his UDF
coalition partner, to discuss ways to help unite the conservative government
and parliamentary majority 'with a view to the presidential election'.
Yesterday, Mr Chirac made it clear that he was not going to answer any
summons from Mr Balladur before convening top leaders of the RPR, which he
dominates, to discuss the strains that presidential rivalries are placing on
the government. A close Chirac aide, Mr Eric Raoult, complained yesterday
that Mr Balladur was trying to gag Mr Chirac's supporters while giving free
voice to his own.
Mr Giscard d'Estaing yesterday claimed that his UDF federation was not to
blame for the recent political ructions, implying he had nothing to discuss
with Mr Balladur.
Mr Balladur's appeal for presidential campaigning to be delayed until the
New Year looks likely to go unheeded, partly because his rivals see it as
self-serving.
