<HEADLINE>
FT  20 OCT 94 / Kuchma wins reform vote
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MATTHEW KAMINSKI
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   KIEV
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Ukraine's parliament yesterday endorsed, by a surprisingly wide margin,
President Leonid Kuchma's economic reform programme. The vote suggests the
Communist-dominated parliament will not for now spoil the first attempt at
real reform in the depressed former Soviet republic. Mr Kuchma now has the
chance to implement the tough macroeconomic steps required to secure
Ukraine's first Dollars 360m credit from the International Monetary Fund,
which due to approve the loan next week. Before then, Ukraine must unify
currency exchange rates and liberalise prices, among other reforms. Nine
decrees are awaiting Mr Kuchma's signature, say advisers.
Initial steps are likely to stoke inflation and further devalue the unstable
currency. But the IMF credit, a interest rate and foreign aid - to be
discussed at a special meeting in Canada next week of the Group of Seven
industrial nations - would help offset the devaluation. Price
liberalisation, covering coal and natural gas, also would enable the
government to reduce subsidies to close the 1994 budget deficit to 10 per
cent of gross domestic product.
