<HEADLINE>
FT  19 OCT 94 / International Company News: Surge in ADM earnings
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURIE MORSE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   CHICAGO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Archer Daniels Midland, the agribusiness concern based in Decatur, Illinois,
said its first-quarter earnings rose to Dollars 154.5m, or 45 cents a share,
up from last year's Dollars 69m, or 20 cents, when floods in the Midwest
impaired operations. The results exceeded Wall Street estimates.
With its commodity-based businesses, ADM does not report sales with its
quarterly earnings. However, analysts said that the company's two most
important business segments - corn processing and soyabean crushing - were
profiting from low raw materials prices and growing international demand for
vegetable oils and high fructose corn syrup.
Ms Bonnie Wittenburg, an agribusiness analyst for Dain Bosworth in
Minneapolis, raised her full-year earnings projection for ADM to Dollars
2.00 a share from Dollars 1.90 on the basis of the first-quarter report, and
expects the company to earn Dollars 2.40 a share next year.
