<HEADLINE>
FT  19 OCT 94 / International Company News: Repola and Kymmene return to
black - Finnish groups' results confirm this year's recovery in Nordic
forestry industry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HUGH CARNEGY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   STOCKHOLM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Repola and Kymmene, two of Finland's big four forestry groups, yesterday
reported large swings back to profit in the first eight months of the year
after losses in the same period last year. The recovery followed sharply
reduced financial charges.
Both reported high capacity utilisation - 94 per cent in the case of
Kymmene's paper mills - and said demand in Europe for forestry products and
paper was likely to remain strong.
The results were in line with resurgent profitability in the Nordic forestry
industry this year. They covered a period during which Repola and Kymmene
came close to agreeing a merger between Kymmene and United Paper Mills, the
forestry group and main component of Repola. Talks broke down in June.
Repola reported pre-tax profits in the first eight months of FM1.17bn
(Dollars 252m), a turnround from a restated loss of FM119m in the same
period last year. Repola and Kymmene restated 1993 figures to conform with
European Union accounting principles.
Turnover rose to FM18.36bn from FM17.77bn and operating profit grew to
FM2.11bn from FM1.67bn. Financial expenses fell FM792m due to lower interest
rates and a reduction in group debts.
Operating profits at UPM rose to FM1.8bn from FM1.48bn on turnover up at
FM12.56bn from FM11.74bn. Repola said the increase in turnover was due to
marked growth in its paper and mechanical wood processing businesses.
Repola's engineering division, Rauma, saw sales increase to FM5.18bn from
FM5.03bn. But operating profits doubled to FM247m from FM124m.
At Kymmene, there was a swing to a FM545m profit in the first eight months
from a FM337m (restated) loss. Sales rose to FM12.11bn from FM10.98bn,
thanks mainly to higher sales of fine papers, panels and sawn timber. Value
of sales fell FM700m as the markka appreciated.
Operating profit rose to FM1.32bn from FM944bn. Net financial charges
tumbled to FM846m from FM1.2bn.
</TEXT>
