<HEADLINE>
FT  19 OCT 94 / Blair tackles Tories over split on Europe
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Tony Blair used his first Commons appearance as Labour leader yesterday
to resurrect the option of a referendum on the next stage of EU integration.
Mr Blair, launching a fresh assault on Conservative divisions on Europe,
sought to extract some of the traditional heat from question time by
offering an unqualified endorsement of Mr John Major's Ulster policy.
In what aides described as a deliberate attempt to raise the tone of the
twice-weekly question time confrontation, he addressed the prime minister in
cautiously modulated tones, and restricted himself to two questions rather
than three.
Mr Major, who also dislikes the gladiatorial aspects of question time,
congratulated Mr Blair on his new job, prompting most observers to score the
first confrontation between the two leaders as a draw.
Mr Blair appeared to surprise Mr Major by challenging him to disown comments
by Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, ruling out a referendum on monetary
integration as 'a very strange way to run a modern industrial state'.
Mr Major said that the issue of a referendum 'does not arise and very
probably will not arise' because the agenda for the 1996 intergovernmental
conference of EU states had not been set.
Ridiculing Labour's pro-EU approach, he accused Mr Blair of seeking to form
a 'weak' government that would 'slavishly follow whatever Europe says'.
But Mr Blair told him: 'The chancellor takes one view on Europe, the
employment secretary (Mr Michael Portillo) takes another view, and you hover
between the two. A divided government is a weak government.'
Mr Blair gave no hint of a change in Labour policy on a referendum, which
mirrors the government's official view that no decision is necessary until
firm decisions have been made on whether to join a single European currency.
However, friends said he was considering promising a referendum in an
attempt to force Mr Major to endorse or reject demands for a vote by the
Tories' powerful Euro-sceptic wing.
Labour leaders are keenly aware that demands for a referendum caused Mr
Major anxiety when they were pressed by Conservative Euro-sceptics before
the European elections in May. A referendum is strongly opposed by Tory
pro-Europeans, who believe it would exacerbate party splits and lead to a
divisive campaign that could bring down the government.
Tory strategists believe a referendum is equally dangerous for Labour
because it could inflame the party's own Euro-sceptics.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
