<HEADLINE>
FT  19 OCT 94 / Yeltsin in conflict with Russian prime minister: Economic
policies cause rift in leadership
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN LLOYD
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A serious rift has opened up between Russia's president Boris Yeltsin and
his prime minister, Mr Victor Chernomyrdin, whom he holds partly to blame
for the recent steep fall in the value of the rouble.
The two leaders differ over a range of economic policy issues. Mr
Chernomyrdin's continued absence from Moscow is a sign that he is regarded
with deep disfavour by President Yeltsin. Mr Chernomyrdin, who is still
officially on holiday at Sochi on the Black Sea, had been scheduled to
welcome the Queen in Moscow on Monday.
A report carried by independent radio and TV stations that Mr Chernomyrdin
had submitted his resignation was quickly denied by government spokesmen
yesterday. Mr Chernomyrdin himself told US vice-president Al Gore during a
scheduled phone conversation last night that the resignation rumours - which
had reached the White House - were untrue.
However, the prime minister was said to be preparing a statement to
journalists today.
A report by the Security Council - the standing commission which oversees
security matters - on the fall of the rouble was debated by the council
yesterday, but no formal announcement was made afterwards except that it
would continue its work for a further two weeks.
However the report is believed to put some of the blame for the rouble's
fall on the prime minister, as well as on Mr Victor Gerashchenko, chairman
of the central bank, and on Mr Sergei Dubinin, the acting finance minister -
both of whom have resigned.
Mr Sergei Shakhrai, the deputy prime minister for nationalities policy, said
yesterday: 'Any official who had a part to play in the rouble's fall has to
take responsibility for whatever area he has under his control.' He said
that the resignation of Mr Gerashchenko, a man with many allies in the
parliament, could 'create such a critical situation in which a discussion of
the budget in the duma (lower house) could have negative results for the
government'.
Mr Shakhrai, a close ally of Mr Chernomyrdin's in the past, said that he
believed that in spite of the blow it had received, 'the Chernomyrdin
government will remain in power'. He added, however, that an investigation
was continuing and that criminal charges might be brought.
The tension between Mr Yeltsin and Mr Chernomyrdin has grown in recent
months, as the president sought to ease Mr Chernomyrdin's tight credit and
monetary policy.
Mr Yeltsin has in recent months pointedly preferred to consult Mr Oleg
Soskovets, first deputy prime minister, who accompanied him on his trip to
the US last month.
The Russian president yesterday named Ms Tatyana Paramonova, a former deputy
chairman in charge of budget and credit policy, as the central bank's acting
chairman.
Ms Paramonova has a high reputation for her tough views on the need for a
tight credit policy and for control of inflation. However, her relative
youth - she is 44 - and her sex, as well as her recent accession to a high
position in the bank, in 1992, has convinced most observers that she is a
temporary leader.
</TEXT>
