FT  19 OCT 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Having been knocked off my motorbike a few months ago, with consequent
broken ribs and a damaged leg, I shall watch Dispatches with particular
interest (9.00 C4). We are promised examples of the increasingly
questionable methods used by insurance companies in their determination to
avoid paying damages. It seems that private detectives posed as market
researchers, for instance, and tried to get Lynn MacDonald to undertake
cleaning work incompatible with her medical condition so that they could
secretly film her doing it. Lovely people. Highlight of the evening is the
return of Between The Lines, the most impressive police series to have
appeared in the past 10 years (9.30 BBC1). Bravely the producers have
decided to take a major sideways jump in the plot, moving Clark not only out
of the internal investigation bureau but right out of the Met. He finds
himself working undercover for the Sun. The opening programme in C4's
Counter Culture (the title is a pun) was about a tea and coffee merchant.
Today's shop is the one in Newcastle United's stadium (9.45).
