FT  19 OCT 94 / Howard at International Police Exhibition and Conference
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Michael Howard, the home secretary, yesterday tested a viewer for
recording scenes of crime in 3-D at the International Police Exhibition and
Conference at Olympia, London.
At the conference Mr Howard announced a plan to invite crime-hit communities
to bid for Pounds 2m from the government - complemented by private and
public sponsorship - to install closed circuit television systems.
Housing estates, shopping centres, hospitals and car parks will be eligible
to submit bids. Mr Howard said the government would only be looking for
applications from smaller communities and local neighbourhoods since large
towns and cities had already received support for the systems. Bids have to
be submitted by next month. The maximum that schemes will receive is Pounds
100,000. Mr Howard said: 'Given the success of CCTV in many parts of the
country in preventing crime and increasing arrests for crimes committed,
this is an important development.'
