<HEADLINE>
FT  19 OCT 94 / DTI may reform Whitehall pensions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government is considering replacing final salary-based pension benefits
for civil servants with less costly personal pensions, it was revealed
yesterday.
The allegations were made by Ms Elizabeth Symons, general secretary of the
Association of First Division Civil Servants, who obtained a leaked copy of
a letter from Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and industry secretary.
The letter, addressed to Mr Jonathan Aitken, chief secretary to the
Treasury, and circulated to cabinet members, said Mr Heseltine's department
would 'look at the issue of portable/personal schemes'.
The move comes as the government faces growing embarrassment over its
failure to control the mis-selling of personal pensions. Up to 500,000
people may have been wrongly advised to transfer out of sound occupational
schemes into personal pensions.
While personal pensions are deemed beneficial for the self-employed and for
those who change jobs frequently, they are considered less advantageous for
those who stay in the same job longer.
The letter also says that the Department of Trade and Industry is
considering selling off the administration of its own employees' pension
scheme. This is in spite of a 1992 report from the Treasury's Efficiency
Unit which concluded that the scheme is administered as efficiently as any
in the private sector.
</TEXT>
