<HEADLINE>
FT  19 OCT 94 / Print union calls off 18-month strike
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND ADBURGHAM, Wales and West Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Industrial action against the Bristol printing company JW Arrowsmith will be
called off today after 18 months of picketing. It has been the longest
dispute in the city's history.
Arrowsmith dismissed 120 employees in April last year after they voted to
take industrial action in pursuit of a national pay claim. At the same time
it derecognised their union, the GPMU.
In spite of an official picket ever since, the family-owned company has
stayed in business and the GPMU has failed to make it negotiate. But the
company has reduced in size and is seeking to sell its site in south Bristol
and move to smaller premises.
Mr John Monks, general secretary of the Trades Union Congress, said last
night that the sacked workers' struggle had inspired trade unionists across
the country. He said the dispute 'should serve to show other employers that
such shortsighted, unjust and anti-union management is no way to build a
successful business'.
Arrowsmith, which was founded in the mid-19th century and specialises in
technical typesetting, dismissed the staff for breach of contract. The
company, which made a loss the previous year, said it had been damaged by an
overtime ban and could not afford the claim for Pounds 6.50 a week and an
extra day's holiday.
It offered to re-employ staff on personal contracts and with a pay freeze,
but only a handful returned.
</TEXT>
