<HEADLINE>
FT  19 OCT 94 / Level of injury pay-outs attacked
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE, Legal Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Compensation for personal injuries in England and Wales is often inadequate
according to research by the Law Commission published yesterday.
It said delays of six years or more in settling claims meant damages were
eaten up by debts and extra expenses incurred before settlement.
The commission surveyed more than 750 victims of accidents occurring between
1967 and 1991. They had received compensation from Pounds 5,000 to Pounds
100,000 or more.
The commission found minor injuries could have unexpectedly severe
consequences and serious injuries did not necessarily result in big
settlements.
More than 50 per cent of victims in work at the time of the accident never
returned to the same job and a substantial minority never returned to work.
Almost 90 per cent of those receiving damages of Pounds 100,000 or more left
their job as a result of the accident. Many victims who did return were
forced to leave owing to the continuing effects of their injuries.
This resulted in a significant burden of unpaid care being shouldered by
family or friends.
Although most victims were satisfied at the time of settlement with what
appeared to be a substantial sum of money, this satisfaction decreased
dramatically as they realised the long-term effects of their injuries and
their reduced capacity to work.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9441 Administration of Social and Manpower Programs.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>NEWS  General News.
</TP>
