<HEADLINE>
FT  19 OCT 94 / Property deals pull in Pounds 230m for new-towns commission
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SIMON LONDON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Commission for the New Towns, the government agency which owns the
remaining public assets of England's 21 former new towns, raised Pounds 230m
cash in the year to the end of March, up from Pounds 160m.
In July last year Mr John Gummer, the environment secretary, said that the
commission would be wound up by March 1998. It has already been split into
two slimmed-down agencies responsible for marketing the remaining land and
buildings.
The commission's annual report, published yesterday, shows commercial
property sales valued at Pounds 130m. A further Pounds 111m came from the
transfer of housing assets to the local authority and housing associations
in Basildon.
After tax and loan interest the commission returned Pounds 117m to the
government, bringing its total contributions to the Exchequer in the past
five years to Pounds 867m. The commission made 500 sales during the year,
compared with 430 in 1992-93.
Sir Neil Shields, chairman, said market conditions had improved since the
begining of the financial year and that Pounds 95m from commercial
transactions had already been received.
He estimated that receipts for the current full year would be about Pounds
162m.
The commission still owns 2.5m sq ft of commercial and industrial floor
space and 19,000 acres of land. Most of its remaining assets are in Milton
Keynes and former new towns in the North and Midlands, such as Telford and
Warrington.
Holdings in the former new towns surrounding London have dwindled. Excluding
the Basildon housing transaction, which involved the transfer of 13,000
homes and leaves the CNT with virtually no residential housing, receipts
from towns in Southern England amounted to only Pounds 35m.
The commission employs 450 people, down from a peak of 1,100 during the mid
1980s. The number of employees is projected to fall to 220 by 1997/98.
</TEXT>
