<HEADLINE>
FT  19 OCT 94 / London to lure back investment
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BAXTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A drive to attract more manufacturing investment to greater London was
launched yesterday by Mr Tim Eggar, industry and energy minister, in a move
that marks the first concerted attempt to reverse the decline of the capital
as a manufacturing centre.
The greater London manufacturing workforce has dropped from more than
800,000 in the early 1970s to 300,000. This is just 11 per cent of the
area's total workforce, compared with a nationwide figure of 20 per cent.
Mr Eggar's initiative also aims to ensure existing manufacturers get the
best deal from central and local government. It comes a day after Samsung,
the Korean industrial group, announced plans to build a Pounds 450m
manufacturing plant in the north-east of England, eventually creating 3,000
jobs.
He said this showed how development agencies, local authorities and Training
and Enterprise Councils elsewhere in the UK were working effectively with
government to attract new manufacturers. 'Other regions of the UK are old
hands at this,' he told the parliamentary manufacturing industry group.
Mr Eggar, MP for Enfield North, said London could not escape blame for
undervaluing its manufacturing sector. 'The false stereotype of the London
businessman with his pinstriped suit and bowler hat has been equally
misleadingly replaced by the image of a young man with red braces
wheeler-dealing in front of an exchange room computer screen,' he said.
An anti-manufacturing culture had been perpetuated. Companies faced with the
opportunity to expand had found it easier to move elsewhere rather than work
through the issues with their local workforce, local authorities and
government.
Mr Eggar said the government could not prescribe a recipe for success.
Instead, central government, local authorities, agencies such as the London
First forum and companies needed to work together to ensure that London
thrived as a base for manufacturing.
As a first step, he plans to bring together some of the capital's most
important manufacturers to agree priorities for action.
But he identified three key issues which he said London needed to address
urgently:
TECs must ensure that the skills of London's workforce match industry's
needs.
Boroughs need a proactive programme to nurture manufacturing industry.
Local business organisations need to foster supply chains and ensure that
the new London Business Links organisation gives clients a better advisory
service than is now available.
</TEXT>
