<HEADLINE>
FT  19 OCT 94 / Judge calls for fraud tribunal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE, Legal Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A tribunal to deal with all criminal, civil and regulatory aspects of
serious fraud was called for yesterday by the former judge in the Guinness
trials.
Lord Justice Henry, who presided over the trials arising from the 1986
Guinness takeover of Distillers, told a fraud forum that the need to avoid
duplication of investigation and adjudication in white-collar crime pointed
to the creation of 'forensic one-stop-shopping' for fraud cases.
He said that issues of guilt, punishment by imprisonment or fine, civil
liability, payment of damages and restrictions on companies' ability to
continue in business should all be adjudicated in one process.
He added that the closest the western world had to such a model was the
Securities and Exchange Commission in the US where, within a statutory
framework of racketeering laws much more hostile than anything in the UK, a
commission suggestion of a plea-bargain became an offer the defendant could
not refuse.
The US system was 'brutal but effective' and the US racketeering laws could
not be transferred entirely to the UK.
The judge said, however, that there was one seemingly fatal objection to his
proposal in that if a defendant pleaded not guilty he could not be sentenced
to more than 12 months in jail without being convicted by a jury.
As juries did not give reasons for their verdicts a jury's criminal verdict
was not sufficiently discriminating to try all the issues which would be
involved in one-stop-shopping.
He said the solution might be for fraud cases to be tried by a judge alone
giving a reasoned judgment. Defendants in serious fraud cases in other
common-law countries, such as New Zealand and Canada, were being offered the
choice of being tried by a judge.
These trials would, he said, provide all the economies of a single
fact-finding trial. The process would be internally consistent, more
manageable, shorter and cheaper.
It would also have the advantage that any appeal could concentrate on the
validity of the conviction rather than questions of procedural irregularity,
or technical misdirection.
</TEXT>
