<HEADLINE>
FT  19 OCT 94 / Mercury to double its mobile reach
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mercury One-2-One, the mobile phone network operator, is to invest Pounds
230m in doubling the size of its network over the next two and a half years.
The investment, which continues One-2-One's slow expansion, will give the
UK's main population centres four cellular phone networks by early 1997,
making Britain the most competitive market in Europe.
One-2-One currently covers only the south-east and the west Midlands - about
30 per cent of the UK population. The networks of Vodafone and Cellnet, the
two biggest operators, have national coverage. Orange, the newest network,
covers about 65 per cent of the population and plans to extend its coverage
to 70 per cent by the end of the year.
With 140,000 subscribers, One-2-One is small by comparison with Vodafone and
Cellnet, which have about 1.4m and 1.2m subscribers respectively. But the
company claims to be gaining a third of all sales in its coverage area.
Orange, which launched its network in April, refused to disclose subscriber
numbers, prompting speculation among analysts that it was gaining customers
at a slower rate than One-2-One in spite of its wider geographical coverage.
The new investment will extend One-2-One's network to include all of the
Midlands, the north-west, and the south and south-east coast.
Mr Richard Goswell, One-2-One's managing director, said the company did not
intend to cut tariffs or handset prices to attract more subscribers. 'We do
not see any need for a price war. All four operators are comfortable in
their parts of the market,' he said.
Vodafone and Cellnet are also keen to delay serious price competition but
have cut the price of their digital handsets sharply in the past month, to
less than Pounds 100 for the cheapest.
One-2-One's cheapest handsets sell for Pounds 200. Mr Goswell said the
company would not increase subsidies for handsets to reduce the price. 'I
don't believe in giving handsets away. It sends the wrong message about
their value, and we want customers to make decisions based on the long-term
cost of having a mobile phone,' he said.
With more than five mobile phone subscribers per 100 people, the UK has more
usage per head than any European country outside Scandinavia.
Cellnet, a joint venture between British Telecommunications and Securicor,
made the biggest advance of any operator in the quarter to September, with
133,000 net new subscribers compared with 123,000 for Vodafone, which
remains the biggest operator.
The networks of One-2-One, a joint venture between Mercury and US West, and
Orange are built to the PCN standard, which requires the installation of
more radio base stations than the GSM standard used by Cellnet and Vodafone.
</TEXT>
