<HEADLINE>
FT  19 OCT 94 / Feltrim syndicates run by 'gamblers'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON, Law Courts Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Underwriters of three Feltrim syndicates at Lloyd's of London ran their
businesses like imprudent gamblers, the High Court was told yesterday.
The syndicates' total exposures to risk were not properly calculated and
inadequate reinsurance was purchased, said Mr Jeremy Cooke QC, opening the
case for more than 1,600 Feltrim Names.
The Names are suing the underwriters for negligence and are seeking to
recover losses of about Pounds 525m.
The losses were sustained between 1987 and 1989 by syndicates 540, 542 and
847, which specialised in catastrophe insurance. The syndicates suffered
massive losses after disasters such as the 1987 storms and the Piper Alpha
oil platform explosion.
Mr Cooke said the gap between the exposures of the syndicates and the levels
of reinsurance purchased was too big. Nobody running a business prudently
would operate on the basis that if certain events took place the business
would be destroyed, he said. This amounted to simply gambling on whether
those events would happen.
He added: 'Even if gambling, no prudent man would put Pounds 200m on a 100-1
outsider unless he knew he had Pounds 200m available should that 100-1
outsider come home first.'
The case is expected to last until Christmas.
</TEXT>
