<HEADLINE>
FT  19 OCT 94 / Thatcher link claim in papers on Saudi arms
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN and JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Ministers are to study documents which Mr Tam Dalyell, Labour MP for
Linlithgow, claims show that Mr Mark Thatcher was involved in the Al Yamamah
arms deal between the UK and Saudia Arabia while his mother, Baroness
Thatcher, was prime minister.
Mr Dalyell handed the documents, based on a report from from US intelligence
and an internal British Aircraft Corporation memorandum, to officials in the
Commons during the two-day defence debate.
Mr Roger Freeman, minister for defence procurement, said the documents would
be examined, but insisted that the deal was conducted on a
government-to-government basis.
He said: 'No commissions were paid, and no agents or middle men were
involved.'
Mr Dalyell produced the documents after Mr John Major, the prime minister,
challenged MPs who supported allegations that Mr Thatcher had received
Pounds 12m in commissions to produce evidence that could be examined by the
proper authorities.
The prime minister reaffirmed that Lady Thatcher had 'acted with complete
propriety throughout her long and distinguished period as prime minister of
this country'.
Mr Dalyell said the documents highlighted Mr Thatcher's role in the arms
deal, and referred to the part he played in administering a 'sizeable
payment' to the Conservative party.
He challenged a government denial that Sir Clive Whitmore, former permanent
undersecretary at the Ministry of Defence, had told Lady Thatcher of his
disquiet over the involvement of her son in the negotiations on the arms
deal.
Mr Dalyell called for a specific assurance that 'there was no contact on
this issue, official or unofficial, between the permanent secretary to the
Ministry of Defence and the then prime minister'.
Earlier, when Mr Paul Tyler, a Liberal Democrat MP, asked for an assurance
'that your administration is now a sleaze-free zone', Mr Major said: 'I am
as concerned as any member in this House or any person in this country that
we should have the highest standards in public life.'
</TEXT>
