<HEADLINE>
FT  19 OCT 94 / Portillo consolidates EU attack
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Michael Portillo, the employment secretary, yesterday consolidated his
attack on the European Union's social chapter provisions, saying that he
would resist any directives from Brussels that reduced employment in the UK.
As the Labour party launched a new broadside against the government for
refusing to direct UK economic development Mr Portillo said that the only
way to create jobs was by promoting low inflation and a prosperous economic
climate.
Answering Commons questions for the first time since he assumed the
employment portfolio Mr Portillo told MPs: 'I want to make sure we do not
destroy jobs in Britain. I am not prepared to have imposed upon Britain
costs on employers which make them less likely to take people on.'
Mr Portillo's attack came as the Labour party criticised the Department of
Environment's urban regeneration programme, saying that plans to promote
local enterprise were turning into a 'smokescreen for cuts' in public
spending.
Mr Jack Straw, the shadow environment secretary, said the amount of money
being allocated for the Single Regeneration Budget amounted to less than a
quarter of the size of bids made by local authorities and Training and
Enterprise Councils to obtain money under the scheme.
He said that the total allocation for the budget, amounting to Pounds 100m,
had been dwarfed by the overall cuts in funding for urban regeneration over
the next two years, amounting to about Pounds 200m.
Mr Straw said that 469 bids - worth more than Pounds 375m - had been made
for SRB grants in the next financial year.
'Despite its high profile launch earlier this year it is now clear that the
SRB is a gameshow with high entrance fees but very few winners.'
He said that millions of pounds had been wasted in the preparation of bids.
Mr John Prescott, Labour's deputy leader, also joined in the attack on the
government's industrial policies, pledging Labour's active promotion of
information and communications technologies.
He said that Britain had to respond to the revolution in information
technology if it was to compete in the global economy.
He said: 'The white heat of technology in the 1960s has been replaced by the
white light of technology in the 1990s.'
</TEXT>
