<HEADLINE>
FT  19 OCT 94 / New car sales forecast to show 8% rise
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN DONE, Motor Industry Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Ford and Vauxhall forecast yesterday that new car sales in the UK would
total about 1.92m in 1994, an increase of nearly 8 per cent from 1.78m last
year.
The rate of growth has slowed significantly in the last four months, however
 -with private sales particularly weak - forcing carmakers to lower
forecasts for the year.
The leading UK dealer organisation attacked the makers for overpricing cars.
Mr Alan Pulham, director of the National Franchised Dealers' Association,
said that 'prices of new cars could be cut by as much as Pounds 2,000 if
manufacturers abandoned two-tier pricing and stopped adding expensive
specification items purely to influence corporate buyers'.
He added: 'It is not surprising that the retail customer has shown
insufficient confidence to invest in today's overpriced product.'
Prices could be reduced by 10 per cent, or about Pounds 1,000 on an average
saloon car, if manufacturers stopped giving fleet buyers excessive discounts
at the expense of the private buyer, Mr Pulham said.
'The price cut could be doubled if vehicle specifications were made more
relevant to today's market,' he said. '1994 vehicles are grossly
overspecified and as a consequence overpriced.'
Mr Pulham has previously attacked carmakers for distorting the market by
encouraging the pre-registering of cars by dealers in order to gain market
share without the cars having a final buyer.
Mr Charlie Golden, chief executive of Vauxhall, the UK subsidiary of General
Motors, said: 'We were disappointed by the market's activity in the past two
months, but we see no reason to panic.'
Mr Ian McAllister, chairman of Ford of Britain, said that 'according to all
the economic indicators' the recession was finished but 'the message has yet
to get through to the general buying public'.
He called on the UK government to follow France and Spain in introducing
financial incentives to encourage the scrapping of old cars. About 10 per
cent of vehicles - particularly unregulated diesel cars - caused 50 per cent
of vehicle pollution, he said.
'It's time for the government to look at the actions taken in France and
Spain to stimulate sales of new cars and, more importantly, to encourage the
removal of the older vehicles that do most damage.'
The scrapping incentives in France and Spain had had a marked impact on
economic activity and had started to take older cars and vehicles off the
road, Mr McAllister added.
</TEXT>
