<HEADLINE>
FT  19 OCT 94 / Sainsbury chief admits supermarket 'greed'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The chairman of Britain's biggest supermarket group admitted yesterday that
big food retailers had been 'greedy' in the 1980s and allowed prices for
basic foods to 'drift upwards', opening a gap for cut-price discount chains.
Mr David Sainsbury, chairman of J. Sainsbury, also suggested the big grocery
retailers had been wrong to desert town centres, and were finding new ways
of trading successfully from high-street stores as well as out-of-town
superstores.
Mr Sainsbury said at the annual convention of the Institute of Grocery
Distribution that in their rapid expansion since the mid-1980s grocery
retailers had 'allowed the pendulum to swing too far in two areas'.
He said: 'The major food retailers in the 1980s concentrated heavily on
meeting the increasing demands of customers for convenience, service and
quality, and in so doing we allowed the prices on some basic commodities to
drift upwards. This provided an opportunity for discounters to undercut us.'
Over the past year, he said, superstores had cut prices on basic goods and
returned to the 'historical position' where the gross profit on such
products was small 'because the costs of selling them are very low'.
Answering questions after his presentation Mr Sainsbury conceded that
superstore groups had been 'greedy', but joked that this meant trying to
make a profit margin of a few per cent on products such as bread and milk,
on which they previously made virtually no profit.
Mr Sainsbury suggested the big groups had been mesmerised by the efficiency
and popularity of edge-of-town supermarkets, and forgot that there would
always be some business located in town centres.
He added: 'The market did, however, work extremely effectively and a number
of chains, including the discounters, moved in to fill the gap.' Sainsbury
now favoured remodelling and refurbishing town-centre stores to extend their
life, rather than closing them.
Mr Sainsbury's view was echoed by Mr David Reid, finance director of Tesco,
the UK's second biggest food retailer, who said retailers could now achieve
acceptable rates of return from smaller stores.
Mr Sainsbury's comments came as Mr Henrick Gundelach, managing director of
Netto, the Danish discounter which has been operating in the UK since 1990,
said that discount competition in the grocery market would increase.
He told a conference organised by Verdict, the retail research group, that
the number of discount chains would increase from between three and four to
between eight and 10.
</TEXT>
