<HEADLINE>
FT  19 OCT 94 / Tory corruption probe stays private
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Labour MPs yesterday admitted defeat in a campaign to force the Commons
privileges committee to hear corruption allegations against two
Conservatives in public.
The committee's Conservative majority voted to meet in private to hear
evidence that Mr Graham Riddick (Colne Valley) and Mr David Tredinnick
(Bosworth) were prepared to accept Pounds 1,000 to table Commons questions.
Mr Dale Campbell-Savours, the Labour MP for Workington, who was one of the
prime movers behind the establishment of the committee, but is not a member,
said the decision was 'an outrage'.
Labour members of the committee refused to comment on the debate because of
parliamentary rules requiring the proceedings of the committee to be kept
secret.
They appeared deeply unhappy with the decision to sit in private, however.
Some are thought to be considering whether to resign from the committee in
protest.
Labour MPs believe that quitting the committee before it starts its formal
investigation would undermine its authority and raise questions about the
relevance of its findings.
Mr Tony Newton, leader of the Commons and chairman of the committee, said
the decision to sit in private was in line with long-standing conventions.
He said the committee would publish the evidence when its hearings were
concluded, and would decide later whether to consider the wider issues of
parliamentary privilege in public.
Other Conservative members of the committee refused to comment, but one said
privately that the best interests of both MPs - who have strenuously denied
any wrongdoing - would be served by hearing evidence in private.
He said: 'It should not be held in public because we do not think we could
get to the root of the matter, and it would not be beneficial to the two
people under investigation.
'There would be all sorts of press comment on the rights and wrongs of it
before we came out with our own findings.'
</TEXT>
