<HEADLINE>
FT  19 OCT 94 / PSBR cut by surprise tax boost
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MOTOKO RICH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
An unexpected boost in tax receipts brought government borrowing down to
Pounds 4.08bn in September, edging slightly below City forecasts of Pounds
4.3bn.
September's figure brings the public sector borrowing requirement for the
first six months of the financial year to Pounds 19.5bn, down from Pounds
23.9bn in the same period last year, indicating that the Treasury is still
well on course for its forecast of Pounds 36.1bn for the PSBR in 1994-95.
The Central Statistical Office said the rise in tax revenues was largely due
to early payments of corporation tax, which usually are not received until
October. Companies were encouraged to file taxes early by the introduction
of the pay and file scheme, an incentive plan allowing companies to earn
interest on overpayments.
Receipts from taxes, excise duties and other income totalled Pounds 19.26bn
for September, representing a 20 per cent increase from Pounds 16.11bn in
the same month last year. Cash receipts so far this financial year are 8 per
cent up from the previous year.
Mr Don Smith, UK economist at Midland Global Markets, said: 'So far this
year revenue growth has been rather weak. But in the last couple of months
the figures on tax revenues have been very encouraging indeed.'
The government's purse was filled with Pounds 59m in early receipts from the
third call of the third tranche of BT shares. Excluding these privatisation
proceeds the underlying PSBR was Pounds 4.14bn in September and Pounds
21.8bn in the first six months of the year, compared with Pounds 27.4bn in
the same period last year.
Central government borrowing on its own account was Pounds 4.65bn in
September and Pounds 21.7bn for the financial year to date, against Pounds
25.2bn in the same six months last year. The overall public sector figure
was improved by the debt repayments of local authorities and public
corporations.
Cash outlays by the government in September were Pounds 23.9bn, up from
Pounds 22.3bn in September last year and Pounds 20.96bn in August. The
running total for the financial year to date is Pounds 128.0bn, an increase
of 3 1/2 per cent from the same period last year.
Spending by departments was Pounds 21.8bn in September and Pounds 120.1bn in
the first six months of the financial year, only 1 1/2 per cent up from
Pounds 118.4bn in the same months in 1993-94.
Mr Simon Briscoe, UK economist at SG Warburg, said: 'It now appears that
expenditure is picking up more than we had expected so I think this month's
figure will tame some of the more optimistic forecasts for the PSBR this
year.'
Construction orders fell by 5 per cent in the three months to the end of
August, compared with the three months to the end of May, the Department of
the Environment said yesterday.
It added that orders were 5 per cent higher than the same period last year,
suggesting that the slow recovery in construction activity is generally
being maintained.
</TEXT>
