<HEADLINE>
FT  19 OCT 94 / Walker to leave Lloyds for Morgan Stanley post: Deputy
chairman was expected to take over as head of UK bank
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER, Banking Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir David Walker, the deputy chairman of Lloyds Bank who was widely expected
to take over as chairman, is to leave to join the US investment bank Morgan
Stanley.
Sir David's decision means that Lloyds, the most consistently profitable
British bank, must select both a new chairman and a new chief executive
within two and a half years.
Sir David, who is 54, is to become executive chairman of Morgan Stanley in
Europe. He said that he had expected his role at Lloyds to be 'more
executive than is the case', and he was attracted by the idea of a 'wholly
executive and more than full-time job' when approached by Morgan Stanley.
The move could allow Sir Brian Pitman, Lloyds' chief executive, to succeed
Sir Robin Ibbs as chairman.
Sir Robin is due to retire in two years when he is 70. However, it would be
the first time a Lloyds chief executive has become chairman. The post has
traditionally been filled from outside.
Another candidate to succeed Sir Robin may be Sir Richard Greenbury, the
57-year-old chairman of Marks and Spencer, who is a non-executive director
of Lloyds.
Sir David, a former director of the Bank of England and chairman of the
Securities and Investments Board, was thought likely to become chairman
rapidly when he joined Lloyds in 1992, but Sir Robin has stayed longer than
expected.
Sir David said that Sir Robin was 'hale and hearty, and good for another two
and half years'. He did not expect there to be 'any problem at all' in
finding a chairman to succeed him in what was 'a superbly managed
organisation'.
The main uncertainty over management succession at Lloyds concerns Sir
Brian, who is due to step down as chief executive at the end of 1996 after
his term was extended earlier this year. Sir Brian has no obvious internal
successor.
Lloyds emphasised yesterday that it had two years to make decisions on
management succession. One director said that there was 'no rush' for the
board to choose successors, and that no decision on either post was
imminent.
Lloyds emerged as the most profitable of the 'big four' clearing banks in
the late 1980s. It is trying to take over Cheltenham &amp; Gloucester Building
Society for Pounds 1.8bn as part of its effort to expand retail banking.
Mr Richard Fisher, chairman of Morgan Stanley, said that Sir David, who will
be a member of the firm's New York board, would bring both 'a wealth of
experience' and 'extensive relationships with key figures'.
Morgan Stanley has grown rapidly in Europe in the past two years and
generated Dollars 1.25bn (Pounds 790m) of revenues there last year. Some
directors expect it to double its European business within the next two or
three years.
Observer, Page 23
Why Walker has changed horses, Page 26
</TEXT>
