<HEADLINE>
FT  18 OCT 94 / Activity in homes market declines
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SIMON LONDON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Activity in the housing market declined last month, the Royal Institution of
Chartered Surveyors said yesterday.
Its survey of estate agents mirrors research by other business groups which
suggested that the modest rise in activity over the summer has not been
sustained.
Nearly 60 per cent of the 127 agents included in the institution's survey
said that pre-purchase activity such as inquiries and viewings declined
during the month. Just 16 per cent said that activity had increased while 24
per cent reported no change.
A survey last week by the National Association of Estate Agents found
two-thirds of its members reporting lower activity last month.
Three-quarters of the agents questioned by the institution said that house
prices remained stable, although 15 per cent reported a decline.
Mr Peter Miller of the institution said: 'Optimism about the short-term
prospects for the housing market recovery has seeped away as the anticipated
autumn pick-up in most areas simply failed to happen.'
He added: 'It is now clear that neither house prices nor market volumes will
increase until the new year at the earliest.' Mr Miller said that while the
rise in interest rates had deterred some potential buyers, local factors
were more important than national trends.
The Halifax index showed prices rising slightly in the south in the past
three months but falling in the north.
The survey shows marked variations in housing market conditions even in
neighbouring towns, depending on their local economic fortunes.
Mr Robert Thomas, housing market analyst at UBS, the stockbroking group,
said that in spite of regional variations, the evidence pointed
unambiguously to a weaker market.
He said: 'The relative weakness of personal disposable income following this
year's tax increases and the psychological effect of higher interest rates
have clearly had an impact.'
Housing Market Survey. Royal Institution of Chartered Surveyors, 12 Great
George Street, London SW1P 3AD. Pounds 10.
</TEXT>
