<HEADLINE>
FT  18 OCT 94 / London Stock Exchange: Spotlight falls on BAe
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEVE THOMPSON, PETER JOHN and JEFFREY BROWN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The spotlight in the VSEL takeover saga swung away from the submarine maker
yesterday, to beam full square on British Aerospace following weekend press
reports that BAe might itself end up the victim of GEC's huge cash balances.
BAe, which has an agreed offer for VSEL on the table, surged 28 to 498p in
turnover of 5.9m, at which level its market capitalisation is around Pounds
1.87bn. At the last count GEC was known to be sitting on cash funds of some
Pounds 3bn.
GEC, which last week declared itself as a potential counter-bidder for VSEL,
is widely understood to have held talks last year aimed at merging its
defence business with that of BAe.
GEC opted to play its cards close to its chest yesterday, putting out a firm
no comment statement. The shares rose 2 to 295p in turnover which at 3.1m
suggested that the rumour mill was not having too great an effect on
activity.
VSEL dipped 5 to 1320p following half-year results which included an
increased interim dividend and a declaration that September cash balances
stood at Pounds 364m.
</TEXT>
